        en: `<b>Basic Facts</b><br>• Chemical Symbol — Tl<br>• Atomic Number — 81<br>• A soft, malleable, silvery-grey post-transition metal<br>• Named after the Greek word 'thallos' (green shoot) due to its bright green spectral line<br>• Highly toxic: once used extensively as a rodenticide and ant killer<br>• Critical for specialized high-refractive index glass and IR sensors<br>• Tarnishes quickly in air, resembling lead in appearance<br><br><b>Atomic Structure</b><br>• 81 protons in the nucleus<br>• 81 electrons around the nucleus<br>• Most common stable isotope has 124 neutrons (Thallium-205)<br>• Electron configuration — [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² 6p¹<br>• Located in the 6th period and group 13 of the periodic table<br><br><b>Physical Properties</b><br>• Silvery-white luster when fresh; turns bluish-grey upon exposure to air<br>• Boiling point — 1473°C<br>• Melting point — 304°C (relatively low for a metal)<br>• High density (approx. 11.85 g/cm³) and typical metallic conductivity<br>• Extremely soft: can be cut with a knife at room temperature<br>• Diamagnetic at room temperature<br>• High electrical resistance compared to most other metals<br><br><b>Chemical Properties</b><br>• Reacts with oxygen and moisture to form Thallium(I) oxide and hydroxide<br>• Exhibits stable +1 and +3 oxidation states (+1 is more stable/common)<br>• Dissolves easily in nitric and sulfuric acids; slow reaction with hydrochloric acid<br>• Forms stable halides and specialized organometallic compounds<br>• Thallium(I) compounds behave similarly to alkali metals (K, Rb)<br>• Thallium(III) compounds are strong oxidizing agents and behave like Al or Ga<br><br><b>Thallium Isotopes</b><br>• Thallium has 2 stable natural isotopes: Thallium-203 and Thallium-205<br>• Thallium-205 (²⁰⁵Tl) — most abundant stable isotope (70.48%)<br>• Thallium-201 (²⁰¹Tl) — radioactive, used in medical heart stress tests (scintigraphy)<br>• Over 35 artificial radioisotopes exist, used for specialized research<br>• Isotope ratios used to track industrial pollution in environmental studies<br><br><b>Occurrence in Nature</b><br>• Found primarily in trace amounts in sulfide ores of zinc, lead, and copper<br>• Occasionally found in minerals like Crookesite and Lorándite<br>• Present in Earth's crust at about 0.7 ppm (relatively rare element)<br>• Never found free in nature; recovered as a byproduct of smelting other metals<br><br><b>Industrial Production</b><br>• Recovered from flue dusts during the smelting of zinc and lead ores<br>• Purified via leaching with sulfuric acid and subsequent precipitation<br>• Metal produced by electrolysis of thallium sulfate or reduction with zinc/sodium<br><br><b>Applications of Thallium</b><br>• Optics: high-refractive index glass for camera lenses and fiber optics<br>• Electronics: specialized infrared (IR) detectors and gamma radiation sensors<br>• Medicine: Thallium-201 used as a radioactive tracer for cardiac imaging<br>• Research: used in high-temperature superconductivity studies<br>• Industry: specialized low-melting alloys and mercury-thallium thermometers<br><br><b>Significance in Science and Biology</b><br>• Historically significant (and notorious) as a potent, odorless poison<br>• Crucial tool for non-invasive diagnostic cardiac medical imaging<br>• Essential material for advanced optical systems and photonics<br>• Important for understanding the behavior of heavy post-transition metals<br><br><b>Interaction with Other Fields</b><br>• Medicine — diagnostic heart imaging and nuclear medicine<br>• Technology — specialized sensors for night vision and radiation detection<br>• Environmental Science — monitoring toxic heavy metal contamination<br>• Chemistry — study of 'inert pair effect' in heavy elements`,
